        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1980-12-24T19:18:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1980-12-24T19:18:00-05:00" n="271"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d271">
                <head>271. Telegram From the Department of State to the Embassy in Haiti<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d271fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Foreign Policy File,
                        D800610–0812. Confidential; Immediate. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_DJ_1">Davis</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_HRB_1"
                            >Howard</persName>; cleared in AID/LA/CAR, <gloss target="#t_ARAECP_1"
                            >ARA/ECP</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_HA_1">HA</gloss>, and EB/OFP;
                        approved by <persName corresp="#p_BJA_1">Bushnell</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1980-12-25T00:18:00+00:00">December 25, 1980, 0018Z</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>339226. Subject: Title III Program for Haiti.</p>
                <p>1. Confidential—Entire text.</p>
                <p>2. Recent human rights developments in Haiti have practical impact on our
                    assistance levels to Haiti.<note n="2" xml:id="d271fn2">See <ref target="#d269"
                            >Document 269</ref>.</note> This is particularly true of Title III
                    program which was not in the <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 81 allocation
                    tables notified to Congress. Under current human rights conditions, Department
                    has determined that Title III program for Haiti can not be justified this year.
                    Pursuant to this decision, Embassy and <gloss target="#t_AID_1">AID</gloss>
                    Mission are instructed to inform appropriate <gloss target="#t_GOH_1"
                        >GOH</gloss> officials:</p>
                <p>—That the deteriorated human rights environment resulting from recent <gloss
                        target="#t_GOH_1">GOH</gloss> actions has made it inappropriate for the
                        <gloss target="#t_USG_1">USG</gloss> to continue discussions about a Title
                    III program with the <gloss target="#t_GOH_1">GOH</gloss> at the present
                    time.</p>
                <p>—Accordingly, there will not be a Title III program for Haiti in <gloss
                        target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 81.</p>
                <p>3. As soon as Embassy has informed <gloss target="#t_GOH_1">GOH</gloss>, please
                    notify Department so we can pass similar message to Amb. <persName
                        corresp="#p_CME_1">Charles</persName>.<note n="3" xml:id="d271fn3">In
                        telegram 438 from Port au Prince, January 26, 1981, the Embassy reported
                        that <persName corresp="#p_KHL_1">Kimelman</persName> met with <persName
                            corresp="#p_DJC_2">Duvalier</persName> on January 26 to inform him of
                        the termination of Title III discussions. (National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Foreign Policy File,
                        D810039–0123)</note>
                </p>
                <p>We wish to keep <persName corresp="#p_CME_1">Charles</persName> informed in order
                    to maintain good communications and protect his position. For same reason, we
                    prefer first to pass notification regarding termination of Title III discussions
                    directly to <gloss target="#t_GOH_1">GOH</gloss> in Port au Prince rather than
                    through Amb. <persName corresp="#p_CME_1">Charles</persName>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MED_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Muskie</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
